notes.note: Yes, Hilda's second line here is very deliberately ironic.
Hilda is notably perceptive - she definitely knows there's something up with Marth by this point, but she's not going to steal Lucina's thunder by revealing her secret
Regarding the first line - Hilda doesn't especially care about the cultural preservation of Brigid, she's just anti-Empire.
Hilda is very biased, and is not willing to take constructive criticism on that fact
I really hope this fires the way I think it should, but if it activates when an expected loser loses, please notify me.
Apocalyptic Flame is a weapon art only usable with Hilda's axe, Freikugel - hence the association with the term.
Hilda knows exactly what Jessie really meant, and is deliberately pretending not to in order to try to throw her off.

The time when Hilda's brother, Holst, was at the Officer's Academy, is approximately when the Dagda and Brigid War occurred. Hilda was initally going to ask Shamir if she was still at Garreg Mach back then as one of the Knights of Seiros, but realises her own mistake halfway through the question.
Haha, irony
I'll be coming back to this when she gets her war outfit, because there's some pretty major lies the church has been feeding everyone that get uncovered after the timeskip
Random thoughts for this line of flirting: Coming back for seconds Stuffing/getting stuffed Hilda is dessert?

The Goddess of Fódlan is technically called Sothis, but since nobody needs to differentiate her from any other deities, she is almost exclusively referred to as "The Goddess", except by those with extensive religious knowledge. Hilda does not have this kind of knowledge, so she only knows her as The Goddess.

Coming from a relatively medieval society, I think sex toys in Fódlan are primarily insertion-based, so Hilda would have little concept of vibrators, hence why she's not mentioning them as an alternative. Feel free to have Meia mention them or not
I, the writer, know about absolute territory, and Hilda understands it as a concept, she just doesn't have a name for it
The land Three Houses is based in uses "x Moon" as the names for their months. Pegasus Moon is February
The first two are references to real supports - Dorothea and Byleth's B support, and Hubert and Bernie's C support
Hilda's trying to figure out if Cheryl's into girls at all, and casually dropping that she isn't in a relationship herself. Feel free to have Cheryl realise this or not
Me, sitting down to write Hilda: "Time to engage with geopoliticical implications that are barely touched on in the work she originates from! That'll be great content for this strip poker game!"

The one about Dimitri is based on an infamous Three Houses take where someone tried to get people to stop making shitposts about Dimitri protecting lesbians because "i know this is haha funny fun joke and not real but he is a man who murders women. not just kills. but murders."[sic]

Putting this here for both my benefit and yours - Hilda's special unit in 3 Houses is called the Goneril Valkyries, and they're an all-women infantry - obviously a great source of discussion for the pair. I plan to make mention of this in-character, but I'm already cramming this line pretty full as-is

pendingLines.line: For Meia; on the topic of warning signs from men

Well, you've had experiences with girls before, right? The warning signs are basically the same, the way I see it. There shouldn't be an issue so long as you're both going into it with respect.
Or the right kind of disrespect, if that's what you're into. I don't judge.

The keys are really the same, no matter what your partner's gender is. If you know what to look out for in a woman, you know what's a red flag for a man, too. You've just got to respect each other.
Or disrespect each other in the right way, if that's what you're into. I don't judge.
